sec.p:
In the BC5S2 population, the linear model used for the phenotype Y of an individual was: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
$$ Y_{{i(j)}} = \mu + X_{{i(j)}} \alpha _{j} + e_{i} \quad [{\text{model}}\;1] $$\end{document}where μ is the population mean, Xi(j) is the number of SH alleles at the major locus for individual i(j) and αj is the effect of one allele of the major QTL. This effect differs according to j, the genotypic status of the minor QTL. j = 1 (i = 1, …, 61) when the minor QTL is homozygous SL; j = 2 (i = 1, …, 21) when the minor QTL is heterozygous and j = 3 (i = 1, …, 24) when the minor QTL is homozygous SH. ei is the residual.

In the F2 population used for the mapping of two parthenocarpy QTLs, the model used for the phenotype Y of an individual was the factorial combination of the two loci: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
$$ Y = \mu + X_{1} X_{2} + e\quad [{\text{model}}\;2] $$\end{document}where μ is the population mean, X1X2 is the effect of the combinations of the two parthenocarpy QTLs and e is the residual.
